detail_description: Piazza del Campo is a must-visit destination in Siena, Italy. This historic square has been the city's focal point since the 14th century and offers a unique nine-segment shell shape. Surrounded by notable landmarks such as Palazzo Civico, Torre del Mangia, and Fonte Gaia, visitors can immerse themselves in the daily life of the city.
name: Piazza del Campo
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: 87m-high square stone tower, built from 1325 to 1348, with a belfry dedicated to the Virgin Mary.
detail_description: The Torre del Mangia is an 87-meter-high square stone tower in Siena, Italy, built from 1325 to 1348. It features a belfry dedicated to the Virgin Mary and is a prominent landmark in the city's skyline. The tower is part of the Siena Cathedral complex, which has a rich history dating back to the 9th century. The cathedral underwent significant expansion and renovation over the centuries, resulting in its impressive architectural design.
name: Torre del Mangia
address: Il Campo, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: 1400s frescoes & Renaissance art fill this former hospital, now a museum & exhibition complex.
detail_description: Santa Maria della Scala is a former hospital turned museum and exhibition complex in Siena. The structure, built as a hospital in the 11th century, has been transformed into an extraordinary complex featuring frescoes from the 1400s and Renaissance art. It includes restored pilgrims halls and the chapel of the Madonna, along with new additions such as an archaeological museum, children's museum, modern bar, and bookshop.
name: Santa Maria della Scala
address: Piazza del Duomo, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: 13th century brick town hall with tower housing the civic museum & its fresco collection.
detail_description: Palazzo Pubblico is a 13th-century brick town hall located in Piazza del Campo, Siena. It was built to house the Government of Nine of the Republic of Siena and now serves as the City Hall.
name: Palazzo Pubblico
address: Il Campo, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Siena, a city in central Italy’s Tuscany region, is distinguished by its medieval brick buildings. The fan-shaped central square, Piazza del Campo, is the site of the Palazzo Pubblico, the Gothic town hall, and Torre del Mangia, a slender 14th-century tower with sweeping views from its distinctive white crown. The city’s 17 historic “contrade” (districts) extend outward from the piazza.
detail_description: Siena, located in Tuscany, Italy, is known for its medieval brick buildings and historic landmarks. The city's central square, Piazza del Campo, features the Palazzo Pubblico and the Torre del Mangia. Siena Cathedral is a prominent place of worship with a rich history dating back to the 9th century.
name: Siena
address: 53100 Province of Siena, Italy

excerpt: Severe Gothic cathedral with a frescoed chapel housing relics of St Catherine, including her head.
detail_description: Basilica Cateriniana San Domenico is a striking Gothic cathedral in Siena, Italy. Built in the 13th century, it is renowned for its association with St. Catherine of Siena, who was declared a patron saint of Italy. The basilica houses a frescoed chapel displaying relics of St. Catherine, including her head and finger on a marble altar from 1469.
name: Basilica Cateriniana San Domenico
address: Piazza S. Domenico, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: 13th-century structure famed for its facade & its marble stripes in symbolic black & white.
detail_description: Siena Cathedral, also known as the Duomo, is a 13th-century marvel renowned for its striking facade with symbolic black and white marble stripes. It stands as the main place of worship in Siena and dominates the city's skyline alongside the Torre del Mangia. The cathedral has a rich history, originally built to replace a church dedicated to Mary on a site that was once a temple for the worship of Minerva.
name: Siena Cathedral
address: Piazza del Duomo, 8, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Monumental fountain in a plaza with Old Testament reliefs & statues such as a Madonna & Child.
detail_description: Bar Ristorante Fonte Gaia is nestled in the heart of Siena, right by the iconic Piazza del Campo. This vibrant spot not only offers a delightful dining experience but also immerses visitors in the rich history surrounding it. The nearby monumental fountain, known as Fonte Gaia, is a beloved symbol for locals and features stunning reliefs and statues that tell biblical stories.
name: Bar Ristorante Fonte Gaia
address: Il Campo, 21/23, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Gallery housing vast collection of Sienese masterpieces from the late medieval to Renaissance era.
detail_description: The Pinacoteca Nazionale di Siena is a must-visit for art enthusiasts, showcasing a vast collection of Sienese masterpieces from the late medieval to Renaissance era. Housed in the medieval Palazzo Bonsignori, this national museum features works by renowned artists such as Domenico Beccafumi, Duccio di Buoninsegna, and Michelino Molinari da Besozzo.
name: Pinacoteca Nazionale di Siena
address: Via S. Pietro, 29, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Majestic, airy library within the Siena Duomo known for its soaring, vibrant Pinturicchio frescoes.
detail_description: The Piccolomini Library is a stunning and airy library located within the Siena Duomo. It is renowned for its magnificent Pinturicchio frescoes that adorn the walls and vaulted ceiling. These vibrant frescoes depict scenes from the life of Pope Pius II and are considered to be of great art-historical significance.
name: Piccolomini Library
address: Piazza del Duomo, 8, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Observation point atop an unfinished church facade, with views of centuries-old towers & piazzas.
detail_description: Facciatone, located atop an unfinished church facade near the Duomo di Siena, offers a breathtaking panoramic view of Siena and the picturesque Tuscan countryside. Accessible with an admission ticket to the Duomos OPA Museo, this observation point requires climbing several stairs but rewards visitors with stunning vistas of historical landmarks such as the Duomo di Siena, Torre del Mangia, Piazza del Campo, and ancient city walls.
name: Facciatone
address: Piazza del Duomo, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: St Catherine's home, now a sanctuary, with art-filled oratory, church & Catherine's frescoed cell.
detail_description: Santuario Casa di Santa Caterina is a religious complex dedicated to honoring the life of Saint Catherine of Siena, one of Italy's patron saints. The sanctuary encompasses various structures such as an art-filled oratory, church, and Catherine's frescoed cell. It is believed to be built over her original birthplace and offers visitors the opportunity to explore her birth home where she was born in 1347 as the 23rd of 25 children.
name: Santuario Casa di Santa Caterina
address: Costa Sant'Antonio, 6, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Built in 1563, the brick fort offers a park with hiking/biking trails, city views & an amphitheater.
detail_description: Fortezza Medicea, a 16th-century fortification built by the Medici Family in Siena, offers stunning city views and a glimpse into the region's history. Originally designed for defense, it now features gardens and parklands popular for picnics and leisurely strolls. Visitors can explore its exquisite architecture and captivating wall inscriptions for free.
name: Fortezza Medicea
address: Piazza Caduti delle Forze Armate, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Photography is popular at this neo-Gothic 14th-century palace with a large statue in its square.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Siena, Palazzo Salimbeni is a stunning example of 14th-century neo-Gothic architecture that captures the essence of medieval Italy. Originally constructed as a fortress for the affluent Salimbeni family, this historic palace has seen numerous transformations over the centuries. It stands proudly on Piazza Salimbeni, which was revitalized in Renaissance style about 150 years ago by Giuseppe Partini.
name: Palazzo Salimbeni
address: Piazza Salimbeni, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Central square, site of the city's towering, striped cathedral & the iconic Capitoline Wolf column.
detail_description: Piazza del Duomo is a central square in Siena, Italy, known for its towering cathedral and the iconic Capitoline Wolf column. The Duomo of Siena features a stunning floor with intricate mosaics that will be visible during specific periods. This masterpiece, created using the commesso marmoreo technique, is described as the most beautiful and magnificent ever made.
name: Piazza del Duomo
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: San Domenico is a beautiful church located in a cozy Italian town in Tuscany. The facade of the church features baroque details and renovated stained glass windows that depict the Stories of Saint Catherine. The church also houses relics of Saint Catherine of Siena, making it a significant religious site. Additionally, its convenient location offers frequent services to Florence. Visitors can also find amenities such as toilets available for use at a nominal fee.
name: San Domenico
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Medieval bricked square surrounded by elegant buildings, famous for hosting the Palio horse race.
detail_description: Piazza del Campo, also known as 'Il Campo', is a medieval square in Siena that has been the city's social center since the 12th century. The paving of the square is divided into nine sectors representing the ruling Consiglio dei Nove. It is a popular gathering place for locals and visitors, with cafes around its perimeter offering great spots for coffee and aperitivi.
name: Piazza del Campo
address: Il Campo, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Cathedral baptistry with a bronze relief panel by Donatello on the font, plus 15th-century frescoes.
detail_description: The Battistero di San Giovanni Battista is a significant part of the cathedral complex in Siena, dating back to the early 1300s. The central baptismal font, crafted from marble and bronze with contributions from Donatello, is a remarkable sight. The walls are adorned with frescoes by Vecchietta depicting the Twelve Articles of Faith. Additionally, the baptistery features a Gothic facade with intricate marble patterns and notable works of art inside.
name: Battistero di San Giovanni Battista
address: Piazza S. Giovanni, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: This working 13th-century fountain with Gothic arches & a crenellated roof is fed by aqueducts.
detail_description: Fontebranda, also known as Fontanina Contrada dell'Oca, is a remarkable 13th-century fountain in Siena. It features Gothic arches and a crenellated roof and is supplied by aqueducts. Situated near the Church of San Domenico at Porta di Fontebranda, this medieval fountain boasts three large arches adorned with lion-shaped heads and the emblem of Siena.
name: Fontanina Contrada dell'Oca
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Bar Il Palio is a must-visit spot in Siena, known for its annual horse race, the Palio. The city's Medieval historic center offers picturesque and untouched nature, making it an undeniably scenic destination. Visitors can wander through charming streets, visit museums and architectural gems, and attend events and festivals. During the Palio event at Il Campo, 17 neighborhoods compete in a thrilling horse race around the square, creating an electric atmosphere with spectators from all over the world.
name: Bar Il Palio
address: Il Campo, 47, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Ristorante/pizzeria All'Orto de' Pecci is a unique dining spot located just a short walk from the bustling Piazza del Campo in Siena. The restaurant is set within a tranquil green space that was once part of the Psychiatric Hospital of Siena, where patients tended to fruit and vegetable gardens. Today, this area has been transformed into a peaceful oasis for visitors of all ages to enjoy.
name: Ristorante/pizzeria All'Orto de' Pecci
address: Via Porta Giustizia, 39, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Grand, carved entryway to the city, with a central portico for cars & 2 walkways for pedestrians.
detail_description: Porta Camollia is a magnificent medieval gate that welcomes visitors to Siena's old town. Built in the 13th century, it stands as one of the oldest city gates in Siena and is named after the Roman road Via Camollia. The gate features a central portico for cars and two walkways for pedestrians, showcasing its historical significance and architectural grandeur.
name: Porta Camollia
address: Viale Vittorio Emanuele II, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Palazzo Piccolomini is a stunning example of Renaissance architecture located in the vibrant heart of Siena. Perched on Banchi di Sotto and adjacent to Rinaldini Street, this historic palace offers breathtaking views and is conveniently close to significant sites like the church of San Martino and Palazzo delle Papesse, which also has ties to the influential Piccolomini family.
name: Palazzo Piccolomini
address: Banchi di Sotto, 52, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Palazzo Chigi-Saracini, also known as Palazzo Piccolomini or Palazzo delle Papesse, is a prestigious noble palace located in Siena, Italy. Built between 1460 and 1495 by Caterina Piccolomini, sister of Pope Pius II, the palazzo features a facade reminiscent of Florentine buildings from the same period.
name: Palazzo Chigi-Saracini
address: Via di Città, 89, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Church featuring a gothic brick facade & an uncluttered, marble-banded interior with a wood ceiling.
detail_description: Located near Piazza del Campo, the Basilica of San Francesco is a significant church in Siena. Built in the 13th century in Romanesque style and later expanded into a magnificent Gothic structure, it features a gothic brick facade and a marble-banded interior with a wooden ceiling. The basilica holds historical significance as the site of the Eucharistic miracle of the stolen hosts, which were later found and returned after three centuries.
name: Basilica of San Francesco
address: Piazza S. Francesco, 5, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Piazza del Duomo in Siena is a bustling square filled with historical and cultural attractions. The area is home to the stunning Cathedral of Santa Maria Assunta, featuring an impressive Romanesque-Gothic facade and a remarkable interior with intricate religious symbolism on its floors.
name: Piazza del Duomo
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

name: PALIO DI SIENA PHOTOGRAPHY
address: Via Mentana, 24 A, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Embark on a delightful Chianti wine tour and immerse yourself in the picturesque vineyards and wineries of the renowned Montalcino region. Indulge in the rich history and winemaking traditions as you visit multiple esteemed wineries, sampling a variety of exquisite wines along the way. Learn about the meticulous process of wine production while taking in panoramic views of the stunning Tuscan countryside.
name: Chianti wine tours Wine tour Montalcino
address: Via Paolo Frajese, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

name: Fonti Di Fontebranda
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Piazza Salimbeni is a charming square in Siena, Italy, surrounded by impressive palaces. The Spannocchi palace, built in 1473, represents the city's first Renaissance architecture. On the other side stands the Salimbeni palace, a stunning example of Gothic style and home to Monte dei Paschi, the world's oldest surviving bank founded in 1472. This historic square offers a glimpse into Siena's rich architectural and financial heritage.
name: Piazza Salimbeni
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Nestled just a stone's throw from the iconic Piazza del Campo, Vicolo delle Scotte, 14 is home to Siena's stunning synagogue, an unexpected gem that tells a rich story of the city's past. Dating back to the late 18th century, this architectural marvel showcases a captivating blend of Neoclassical and Rococo styles. Visitors can admire its intricately decorated interior, featuring an exquisite Torah Ark and an Elijah’s Chair from 1860.
name: Vicolo delle Scotte, 14
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Nestled in the serene Valle di Sant'Agostino, the Orto Botanico dell'Università di Siena is a botanical haven that boasts over 2,000 plant species across diverse environments. From tranquil aquatic settings to vibrant rock gardens and enchanting ferneries, this garden offers a delightful exploration of nature. Established in 1784 by the Grand Duke of Tuscany, it has grown significantly over the years and now spans an impressive 2.5 hectares.
name: Orto Botanico dell'Università di Siena
address: Via Pier Andrea Mattioli, 4, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: This 15th-century Renaissance-style church was rebuilt after it was destroyed in World War II.
detail_description: Basilica dell'Osservanza is a 15th-century Renaissance-style church located just two kilometers from the historical center of Siena. It holds great significance as it was once home to San Bernardino. The basilica boasts a collection of remarkable artworks, including an earthenware piece by Andrea della Robbia and a sculpted group depicting the Pieta by Giacomo Cozzarelli.
name: Basilica dell'Osservanza
address: Str. dell'Osservanza, 7, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Il Campo is a captivating central square in the heart of the city, resembling a shell and designed like an amphitheater. It serves as the focal point for various events, most notably the annual Palio horse race, which symbolizes the deep connection between the people of Siena and their city. Despite historical challenges such as war, famine, and plague, this renowned race continues to be celebrated within this remarkable square.
name: Il Campo
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: A lively sightseeing district, Aquila is known for landmarks like 13th-century Siena Cathedral, with its Renaissance statues and frescoed Piccolomini Library. The Pinacoteca Nazionale art gallery displays masterpieces from the Sienese School. Handicraft shops and traditional Tuscan trattorias line Via di Città and nearby streets, while crowds gather twice each summer in the Piazza del Campo for the Palio horse race.
detail_description: Aquila is a vibrant district known for its historical landmarks such as the 13th-century Siena Cathedral and the Pinacoteca Nazionale art gallery. The area is filled with traditional Tuscan trattorias, handicraft shops, and bustling streets like Via di Città. Aquila also hosts the famous Palio horse race in Piazza del Campo twice each summer.
name: Aquila
address: 53100 Siena, Province of Siena, Italy

detail_description: Piazza del Mercato is a bustling square in Siena that offers a vibrant atmosphere and a glimpse into the city's history. Once used for public executions and as a Roman marketplace, it has transformed into a lively hub with diverse merchandise stalls and charming eateries.
name: Piazza del Mercato
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Piazza S. Francesco is a charming square featuring the Franciscan church, where the Sacred Particles have been preserved for nearly 300 years. The square is also home to the Oratory of San Bernardino, which hosts the Diocesan Museum of Sacred Art. This historical site offers visitors a glimpse into centuries-old religious artifacts and architecture.
name: Piazza S. Francesco
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Biblioteca comunale degli Intronati is the main library in the city, offering dedicated spaces for study and reading. The historic building that houses it is worth a visit in itself. Families will appreciate the children's library, which provides a large space with suitable furnishings for young readers and a rich collection of books on open shelves. The library offers an amazing selection of books across all genres and has a fantastic children's section, making it a great place to visit for book lovers of all ages.
name: Biblioteca comunale degli Intronati
address: Via della Sapienza, 1-5, 153100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Siena, the Loggia della Mercanzia is a stunning architectural gem that beautifully showcases the transition from Gothic to Renaissance styles. Constructed between 1417 and 1428, this elegant loggia was originally a bustling hub for merchants who gathered here to conduct their business. Its marble façade is adorned with intricate sculptures of Saint Paul and Saint Peter, crafted by the talented sculptor Vecchietta.
name: Loggia della Mercanzia
address: Il Campo, 78, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Scuola di Cucina di Lella is a highly recommended cooking school in Siena, Italy. The experience begins with excellent communication from Lella and her team, who provide a lovely English translator for an enjoyable and memorable time. The cooking class itself is described as the best meal during travels in Italy, with Lella accommodating schedule changes to ensure a personalized experience.
name: Scuola di Cucina di Lella - Tuscan Cooking Class in Central Siena
address: Via Fontebranda, 69, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Romanesque Catholic church with a 13th-century marble holy-water stoup & Gothic artworks.
detail_description: San Clemente in Santa Maria dei Servi is a stunning Romanesque Catholic church with a 13th-century marble holy-water stoup and Gothic artworks. Situated near Porta Romana, it was initially constructed in the 13th century in Romanesque style and later expanded into a magnificent Gothic structure over the next two centuries.
name: San Clemente in Santa Maria dei Servi
address: Piazza Alessandro Manzoni, 5, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Exploring the narrow laneways of Siena is a must-do activity, offering visitors three distinct areas to wander and discover.
name: Siena
address: 53100 Province of Siena, Italy

detail_description: The Museum of Torture in Siena offers a fascinating and educational experience for visitors. The exhibition features a variety of medieval torture instruments, providing detailed explanations about their use and history. The museum is tastefully curated, avoiding excessive emphasis on blood and gore. It showcases artifacts such as chastity belts, punishment masks, iron maiden sarcophaguses, spiked chairs, vices, and clamps used for torture. Visitors can explore different exhibits that illustrate the various methods of torture employed throughout history.
name: Museum of Torture Siena
address: Chiasso del Bargello, 6, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Insigne Collegiata di Santa Maria in Provenzano is a must-visit attraction located near the fan-shaped Piazza del Campo in Siena. This beautiful church boasts an impressive facade and tasteful interior, making it a worthwhile stop for visitors exploring the historic districts of Siena. Away from the bustling tourist crowds, this hidden gem offers a serene atmosphere and the opportunity to admire the renowned Chiatishire.
name: Chiesa del Santo
address: Piazza Provenzano, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Natural history museum in an old monastery, with taxidermied animals, artifacts & a whale skeleton.
detail_description: Nestled within the charming confines of an ancient monastery, the Musei dell’Accademia dei Fisiocritici offers a captivating glimpse into the wonders of natural history. Established in 1691 by visionary figures like Pirro Maria Gabbrielli and other esteemed professors from the University of Siena, this museum is steeped in a rich tradition of scientific inquiry.
name: Musei dell’Accademia dei Fisiocritici
address: Piazzetta Silvio Gigli, 2, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Azienda Agricola La Lastra is a winery located about 10 minutes from the center of Siena, making it easily accessible for visitors. Guests have raved about the excellent service and hospitality they received during their visits. The owner provides a full tour of the vineyard and olive grove, followed by an exploration of the cellar and a wine tasting experience featuring around 10 delicious wines. Many visitors have also enjoyed homemade meals that perfectly complemented the wines.
name: Azienda Agricola La Lastra
address: Str. della Befana, 2/A, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: The Museo Contrada Priora della Civetta is situated in the heart of Siena and holds the title of Priora due to its historical significance as the location for the first meeting of the Priors of the Seventeen Contrade. Housed near the 13th-century Castellare degli Ugurgieri, this museum boasts a stunning interior adorned with colorful marbles and frescoes by renowned artists Fiorenzo Joni and Bruno Marzi.
name: Museo Contrada Priora della Civetta
address: Via Cecco Angiolieri, 41, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: The Museo dell'acqua in Siena offers an immersive experience to learn about the city's historical water supply system. Interactive exhibits bring to life the various wells and water sources scattered throughout the town. Despite some concerns about the exterior maintenance, visitors praise the knowledgeable guides and their efforts to make the tour enjoyable, even for non-Italian speakers. Overall, it's described as a very interesting and complete visit that provides insight into Siena's water heritage.
name: Museo dell'acqua
address: Str. Fonti di Pescaia, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Located in Siena, Orto Dei Tolomei is a charming garden that offers a lovely view and a peaceful atmosphere away from the crowds. It features benches, outdoor games, and even a gazebo for visitors to enjoy. The park is suitable for children and also serves as an ideal venue for hosting events such as film screenings and concerts. Visitors can take leisurely walks, have picnics, or simply hang out while enjoying the amazing views of the surroundings.
name: Orto Dei Tolomei
address: Via Pier Andrea Mattioli, 7, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

name: Vernice Progetti Culturali Srl Unipersonale
address: Banchi di Sotto, 34, 53100 Siena SI, Italy
